## üìã Prerequisites & Environment Setup

### üîß System Requirements Verification

**üìå Points to Remember:** Before starting any Docker networking lab, always verify your system has sufficient resources and proper Docker installation. Network operations can be resource-intensive and require proper permissions.

```bash
# ‚úÖ Step 1: Verify Docker installation and version
echo "üöÄ Checking Docker installation..."
docker --version
docker-compose --version

# Expected output should show Docker version 20.0+ and Docker Compose version 2.0+
# If not installed, run: sudo apt update && sudo apt install docker.io docker-compose
```

```bash
# ‚úÖ Step 2: Check Docker service status
echo "üîç Verifying Docker service status..."
sudo systemctl status docker

# Expected output: Active (running) status
# If not running: sudo systemctl start docker
```

```bash
# ‚úÖ Step 3: Verify user permissions
echo "üë§ Checking user Docker permissions..."
groups $USER | grep docker

# If 'docker' group not shown, add user to docker group:
# sudo usermod -aG docker $USER
# Then logout/login or restart system
```

```bash
# ‚úÖ Step 4: Test Docker functionality
echo "üß™ Testing basic Docker functionality..."
docker run --rm hello-world

# Expected: "Hello from Docker!" message
# This confirms Docker can pull images and run containers
```

### üíª XFCE Terminal Setup

```bash
# ‚úÖ Step 5: Optimize terminal for lab work
echo "üñ•Ô∏è Setting up optimal terminal environment..."

# Open multiple terminal tabs (Ctrl+Shift+T for new tabs)
# Recommended: 3-4 tabs for monitoring, testing, and main work

# Set terminal to full screen for better visibility
# Press F11 for fullscreen mode
```

### üìÅ Workspace Organization

```bash
# ‚úÖ Step 6: Create dedicated lab workspace
echo "üìÇ Creating Docker networking lab workspace..."
mkdir -p ~/docker-networking-lab
cd ~/docker-networking-lab

# Verify workspace creation
pwd
ls -la

# Expected output: /home/[username]/docker-networking-lab directory
```

